Exploratory Data Analysis: Red Wine Quality

Udacity Data Analyst Nanodegree: Project 4

Author: Ke Zhang

Submission Date: 2017-04-04 (Revision 1)

Abstract

This project performs an exploratory data analysis on the chemical properties influencing the quality of red wines.

  • Link to the red wine quality data set: wineQualityReds.csv
  • Link to the data set description: wineQualityInfo.txt

Structure of the data:

  • There are 13 numeric variables with in total 1599 observations.
  • The variable X is the identifier column which can be ignored in the following analysis.
  • According to the description the variable quality has a value range between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). In this data set there are mainly 5 and 6 ratings.

Well drop X since it is not useful for our analysis.

Create quality levels

Since the most common quality ratings are 5 or 6 and the other ratings have far less data points. We create here a new ordered rating variable for more proper analysis:

  • [0-4]: bad
  • [5-6]: average
  • [7-10]: excellent
##       bad   average excellent 
##        61      1243       211

After the grouping into three categories it appears that most of the red wines are of average quality, followed by excellent, and then bad. Since there are so many average wines the question would be what makes a wine excellent or bad. We will address this issue in the bivariate and multivariate analysis.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

In the data set there are 1599 observations about the variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine and 12 variables about each wine. After the data cleaning phase 84 outliers were removed what leave us 1515 observations left. (Note: The top 1% of outliers were removed from the variables residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide and sulphates.)

Additional to better understand the differences between excellent and bad wines we created an extra ordered variable called rating which summaries the numeric quality values into the three categories: bad, average and excellent.

Lets recheck the data structure:

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Our main goal is to determine what makes a wine taste bad or excellent. So the quality (or rating) is the main feature and the dependent variable. The other 11 attributes are independent variables.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I suspect alcohol, residual sugar and pH value could play a key role in the quality. In my opinion these are the factors which may make wine taste different.

The pearsons correlation may give us a more precise answer. The correlations below are from the independent variables and the quality value. The table identifies alcohol, volatile.acidity and sulphates as the top 3 attributes having the strongest linear correlations with quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

  • I created an ordered rating variable which is a subset of quality based on three distinct categories: bad: [0,4], average: [5,6] and excellent: [7,10]
  • The index variable X was removed because it was not used in the analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  • In the data set we have only quality ratings between 3 and 8. According to the data set description a quality from 0 to 10 is possible.
  • Most of the data points in quality have 5 or 6 as values.
  • The variables residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates had very large numbers. Therefore the top 1% from the values were stripped off.
  • Fixed acidity, sulphates, residual sugar and chlorides all appeared to be long tailed and were log-transformed which revealed a normal distribution for each.
  • Citric acid has many zero values which should be ok after reading the data set description.

Bivariate Plots Section

Correlation Matrix combined with significance test:

Pearsons correlation matrix is a good indicator for linear relationships. Lets examine which variables are correlated with each other:

  • Additional to the correlation heatmap and numbers we crossed the insignificant relationships using corr.test(), p=0.001 and 95% confidence interval.
  • The attribute names are abbreviated to fit into the matrix, e.g. fix for fixed acidity.
  • The variables alcohol, citric acid and sulphates are positively correlated to quality and tend to increase as the quality rating gets higher.
  • The variables volatile acidity, total sulfur dioxide, density, chlorides are negative correlated to quality.
  • The above dependency test shows also that the quality rating is not linear correlated with the variables residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide and pH.
    • The correlation between quality and pH or free sulfur dioxide are only marginal.
    • Residual sugar does not vary with quality.
  • The matrix plot identifies several moderate to strong correlations (abs(corr) >= 0.5) between the independent variables. The one with stronger correlation to quality is bolded:
    • fixed acidity and citric acid
    • fixed acidity and density
    • fixed acidity and pH
    • volatile acidity and citric acid
    • citric acid and pH
    • alcohol and density
    • free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide
  • In the following analysis we may prefer to use the attributes having stronger correlation with quality (marked as bold). The top 5 independent variables ordered by absolute correlation and substitutability:
    • alcohol
    • volatile acidity
    • sulphates
    • total sulfur dioxide
    • chlorides

Relationship between quality and the other independent variables

In the following we use side-by-side box plots to show the relationship between quality and the other independent variables and the differences in the independent variable across levels of quality.

From the side-by-side boxplots certain tendencies can be recognized:

  • Excellent wines tend to have:
    • higher alcohol
    • lower density
    • lower volatile acidity and pH
    • higher citric acid and fixed acidity
    • higher sulphates
  • Bad wines tend to have:
    • lower sulphates
    • higher volatile acidity and pH
    • lower citric acid and fixed acidity
  • Average wines tend to have:
    • higher total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide

Lets save some combinations for the multivariate analysis:

  • alcohol and sulphates to identify excellent wines
    • higher alcohol
    • higher sulphates
  • total sulfur dioxide and sulphates to identify average wines
    • higher total sulfur dioxide
    • average sulphates
  • volatile acidity and sulphates to identify bad wines
    • higher volatile acidity
    • lower sulphates

Analysis using conditional density plot

In the next step we want to analyze some of favored features so far using the conditional density plots.

Conditional density function between alcohol and quality:

  • Excellent wines have an alcohol content between 9 and 15.
  • The probability of being excellent increases with the alcohol content when the alcohol is below 13.5%.
  • Lower alcohol content tends to have more chance being bad.

Conditional density function between pH and quality:

  • An excellent wine quality has a pH value from 2.8 to 3.9.
  • A pH value below 2.8 has almost a 100% chance to be of bad quality.
  • Between pH value of 3.75 and 3.85 the probability of being execellent is at the greatest (~30%)
  • When pH is near 3.9 there is a 50% chance of being bad.

Conditional density function between volatile acidity and quality:

  • An excellent wine quality has a volatile acidity between 0 to 1.0.
  • A volatile acidity above 1.5 is always bad.
  • The probabily of being execellent is at the greatest when volatile acidity is below 0.35(~30%)
  • When volatile acidity is below 0.7 the wine quality is nearly always good or excellent.
  • A volatile acidity near 1.1 is also a bad indicator for good wines.

Conditional density function between sulphates and quality:

  • An excellent wine quality has a sulphates value between 0 to 1.5.
  • A sulphates above 1.5 has no chance of being excellent.
  • When sulphates is below 0.3 or greater than 1.9 the probabily of being bad is at greatest.
  • The chance to be excellent is at greatest when sulphates is near 0.8, 1.0 or 1.4

Create linear regression model

Until now, we have found five major variables from the previous analysis: alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates, total sulfur dioxide and chlorides. Now well try to build a prediction model using linear regression and compare our result with the automatic variable selection using the MASS package.

  • sulphates: 1.4
  • total.sulfur.dioxide: -0.0 (seems to be irrelevant)

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

From the faceted scatter plot and the linear regression model we saw that a higher alcohol, sulphates, and a lower volatile acidity, chlorides might lead to a better wine quality.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

  • In the bivariate analysis we saw only a marginal linear correlation between pH and quality. Due to the strong correlation between the pH and acid variables I decided to take only volatile acidity into the further analysis which had the strongest correlation to quality. In the end however, the linear model using variable selection shows that the pH variable plays also an important role in indicating good wines.
  • In the faceted scatter plots when plotting the main features together, I had expected that the combination of the features would show a more distinctive result. Such as identify bad or excellent wines clearly. However the combination of the variables e.g.using alcohol and volatile acidity had rather a disappointing result. It seems that there were very likely some counteracting effects when combining multiple variables together.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes. I created one linear model using the selected main features from the previous analysis and another one using stepwise variable selection from the MASS package.

The strengths of the linear model are:

  • The linear model is easy to implement and widely used.
  • It shows trends and can even predict outputs beyond the observed data set. (e.g.estimates variables for very excellent qualities 9 or 10)

The limitations of the linear model are:

  • Linear model tries to describe a linear relationship between the variables. Its not sure if the dependency between quality and other main features are really linear.
  • The quality ratings in the data set were all between 3 to 8. And we had relatively few data for very bad or very excellent wines. Its questionable if the data used was sufficient to determine the linear model coefficients.
  • Linear regression is limited to predict numeric variables.
  • Linear regressions are sensitive to outliers.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One: Effect of Alcohol on Quality

Description One: Effect of Alcohol on Quality

This first plot I chose is a side-by-side boxplot showing the relationship between quality and alcohol. I think its interesting because alcohol had the strongest pearson correlation with quality and this boxplot shows clearly how the excellent wines tend to have higher alcohol volumes than the other two groups.

If we only consider the average and excellent wines, the above plot shows clearly that higher alcohol volume yields better wines. The quantiles of bad and average, however, overlap each other somehow. Maybe if we can use some other factors to distinguish between those wines.

Consequently the next time when I go to the wine shop Ill check for wines with a higher alcohol volume.

Plot Two: Combined Effect of Alcohol and Volatile Acidity on Quality

Description Two

In the second plot we demonstrate how the alcohol and volatile acidity affect the quality in a combined way. This plot is interesting because it displays the individual data points for the alcohol and volatile acidity values and uses different colors to show the three quality levels

The plot above shows that blue dots representing wines with excellent qualities tend to concentrate in the left upper corner. This means that excellent wines have lower volatile acidity and higher alcohol The bad wines in other hand tend to be have higher volatile acidity and lower alcohol volume.

Additionally in this plot we see that there are far more wines with average rating than the other two groups. And the average wines seem largely overlaps with both excellent and bad wines in both variables. But if we can be selective, with an alcohol volume higher than 11.5% and a volatile acidity below 0.4g/dm well hardly ever encounter bad wines and have even more than 50% chance to get an excellent bottle.

Description Three: Linear Regression Model

This final plot is perhaps one of the most interesting visualization as it illustrates the relationship between quality and the independent features as a linear model. In the linear model above we used the results from the multivariate analysis and uses the following coefficients:

  • alcohol: 0.3
  • volatile.acidity: -1.1
  • sulphates: 1.4
  • chlorides: -1.7
  • pH: -0.7
  • citric.acid: -0.4
  • (intercept): 4.7

From these plots, we can identify observations 282, 653, 833, 127 and 1375 as possibly problematic to our model. We can look at these observations to see which feature values they have.

The normal QQ-plot compares the quantiles of the standardized residuals to the theoretical quantiles of the linear model. The points follow a mainly linear pattern, suggesting that the data are nearly identical distributed. But in the both ends there are a recognizable amount of points deviating from the theoretical quantiles.

From the lm() output we know that the residual standard error of this model is 0.649 on 1508 degrees of freedom and and adjusted R of 0.364 which says that the linear model fits the data only moderately.

As we discussed in the last optional question, the relationships between the variables of the underlying data might be actually unlinear. It is subject for a further analysis. As I answered that question, another model came up in my mind. I thought about rule-based models maybe the random forest model.

Reflection

In this exercise, we explored the red wine data set on its quality and other physicochemical properties using exploratory data analysis. We have discovered interesting relationships in the data step by step and produced and refines several plots to illustrate them.

It was amazing to see that the alcohol volume had a such big influence on identifying excellent wines which was clearly see in the side-by-side boxplot.

But there were difficulties too during the analysis. In the data visualization phase some struggles happened when plotting with some external libraries which had other behaviors than ggplot2, such as cdplot or corrplot. I had troubles to finetune their colors or font sizes.For example, when I wanted to add the title for the corrplot, only the bottom half of it was displayed in the plot. The feature to merge them into a matrix like using grid.arrange was missing as well.

In the bivariate and multivariate analysis we had problems to differentiate between the bad and average wines. For the future, we might need to dive deeper to investigate in that direction.

Lastly, it should be mentioned that the taste of wine is highly subjective. Different testers might give the same wine different quality ratings. I can even imagine that the same wine could have different ratings by the same tester depending on the day or the mood of the tester. Nevertheless, our analysis could uncover some interesting insights of the wine quality in the available observations.
